I suspect there's a misunderstanding in how EM config interfaces work, and how this needs to be represented in a config.  It should be coming up with it's own type, given that an RDE device has a completely different set of properties than an http satellite device.

With that said, putting some things into a common structure is still valuable even without that, so if you make the changes below, this patch can merge.
Addressing the comments.
Please leave this off until we have another type.
Done
Please use the type safe url type that was used for this previously.  As-written, this is less typesafe than what was there previously.
Done
Added a separate code flow for RDE devices by adding addRdeSatelliteConfig() and other RDE specific functions.

This doesn't seem in line with how we generally do EM interfaces.

Admittedly, this type should probably be called "HttpSatteliteController", and we need a new type for "RdeSatelliteControleller" because they are going to take completely different parameters.  an RDE device doesn't have a "hostname" a "port" nor an "authtype" so there's really no point in reusing this datastructure.

I agree on the type renaming.  Should that be introduced as part of https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/entity-manager/+/61103 to reduce the spread of the current type name?  Or does it need to be its own effort follow-up effort since it's going to require changes in bmcweb and phosphor-dbus-interfaces?
Added a separate code flow for RDE devices by adding addRdeSatelliteConfig() and other RDE specific functions. Now, RDE code does not reuse HTTP's data structures.

This patchset looks like it had a parent that was based on a commit from August 2022.  When rebased (which I did to make sure the log changes got made) this no longer builds because of aggregator changes.  Not sure what's next here.
can you move this variable down to avoid declaration-intialisation seperation? or why do you need it?
why not dbus unpack method?
why is it needed?
std::find_if would be easier to read?

looks like spawning multiple async method. And there is an overwriting behaviour in corresponding response handler in line 977? Does not it depends on the order in which callback are recieved? If response are coming from same demon then why not make single batch request to it?
